      <div xml:id="NA252-kiḷavi">
        <p type="edition">itu poruḷvayiṉ piriyum eṉak kavaṉṟa talaimakaṭkut tōḻi colliyatu.</p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">This is what the confidante said to HER who was anxious that [HE] would separate for the sake of wealth.</p>
        </div>
      <div xml:id="NA252">
        <lg type="edition">
<l>            ulavai yōmai yolkunilai yoṭuṅkic</l>
<l>            ciḷvīṭu kaṟaṅkuñ cēynāṭ ṭattan</l>
<l>            tiṟampuri koḷkaiyō ṭiṟantuceyi ṉalla</l>
<l>            tarumporuṭ kūṭṭa miruntōrk killeṉa</l>
<l>            valiyā neñcam valippac cūḻnta </l>
<l>            viṉaiyiṭai vilaṅkala pōlum puṉaicuvarp</l>
<l>            pāvai yaṉṉa paḻitīr kāṭci</l>
<l>            yaitēyn takaṉṟa valkuṉ maikūrntu</l>
<l>            malarpiṇait taṉṉa māyitaḻ maḻaikkaṇ</l>
<l>            muyalvēṭ ṭeḻunta muṭukuvicaik katanāy </l>
<l>            naṉṉāp puraiyuñ cīṟaṭip</l>
<l>            pomma lōtip puṉaiyiḻai kuṇaṉē.</l>
            </lg>
        <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>It seems they do not obstruct the way of work</l>
<l rend="indent">considered when the heart, that was not hard, became hard,</l>
<l rend="indent4">saying</l>
<l rend="indent">“for those who once were<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">iruntōrkku</term>: the aspect is a little hard to understand. Either we take <term xml:lang="ta">kūṭṭam iruntōr</term> in the sense of a real past tense (i.e. those who have been in union with wealth, but are no longer). Or, and this is supported by T.V.G., we read it as an ellipsis and take <term xml:lang="ta">kūṭṭam</term> as the subject of il: "for those who remain [at home] there is no union with wealth".</note> in union with difficult wealth there is nothing</l>
<l rend="indent">apart from making it [afresh], traversing, with the maxim of acting on</l>
<l rend="indent">reason, the roads to distant lands, where the fierce bee(?) is sounding,</l>
<l rend="indent">being confined to the weakened state of the dry-twigged Ōmai tree,”</l>
<l>– the qualities of [her with] jewels decorating [her] thick hair,</l>
<l rend="indent2">[her] small feet resembling the good tongue<note place="ta">This comparison of a dog’s tongue with feet is probably another one for colour, i.e. red, just like the red lotus. There are several further places in Classical literature where it is made use of, in the older corpus in <term xml:lang="ta">Porunāṟṟuppaṭai</term> 42 and <term xml:lang="ta">Ciṟupāṇāṟṟuppaṭai</term> 17f.</note></l>
<l rend="indent4">of the angry dog of advancing speed that has risen to hunt the hare,</l>
<l rend="indent2">[her] large-petalled rain eyes as blossoms interlinked,</l>
<l rend="indent2">abounding in kajal, [her] wide hips bordering on the wonderful,</l>
<l rend="indent2">[her] sight faultless as an image on a decorated wall.</l>
        </lg>
      </div>
